It was a cold, damp morning when K. received the summons. The document itself was unremarkable, printed on coarse paper with faded ink, yet it demanded his immediate presence at the Ministry of Records, a building he had passed every day but had never seen anyone enter or leave. The summons gave no room number, no official's name, only a timestamp: "At the third hour of the fourth cycle."

When he arrived, K. was confronted by a vast labyrinth of identical wooden doors, each marked with a sequence of numbers that did not follow any discernible order. A clerk sat at a small desk at the end of the corridor, his head buried in a ledger so large it seemed to swallow him. 

"Excuse me," K. said, stepping forward. "I have been summoned here, but the document does not specify where I should report."

The clerk did not look up. "All documents are correct by definition. If your summons lacks a room number, it is because you are expected to find it yourself. The process of searching is itself the beginning of your interrogation."

"But that is absurd," K. replied, his voice echoing in the hollow hallway. "How can I prepare a defense if I do not even know what I am accused of?"

"One does not prepare a defense against the Ministry," the clerk whispered, turning a heavy page that crackled like dry leaves. "The Ministry does not make errors. If you have been summoned, you are already guilty of whatever the record eventually determines. Your only recourse is to wait in the corridor."

Days turned into weeks. K. watched the dust motes dance in the high windows, the pale winter light fading into darkness, then returning. Other citizens sat along the benches, their faces hollow, clutching their own faded slips of paper. Occasionally, a door would open, a name would be called, and someone would disappear into the dim rooms, never to return. The air was thick with the smell of old glue and decaying parchment, the quiet hum of distant typewriters sounding like a swarm of mechanical insects.
